Japan, China, Korea, Malaysia, Singapore: Asia Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-04-13T23:07:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/japan-china-korea-malaysia-singapore-asia-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.4 trillion yen ($28.5
billion) of five-year notes, with the coupon to be disclosed at
10:30 a.m. The ministry will also announce at the same time the
amount of 20-year bonds it will sell on April 21.  The ministry will report at 8:50 a.m. data on local and
foreign investment flows for domestic and overseas securities
for the week ended April 8.  Masayuki Oku, head of the Japanese Bankers Association,
will hold a press briefing at 3 p.m. local time.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was at 1.31 percent, according to  Japan  Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.79 per dollar at 8:03 a.m. in Tokyo.  China :  China Development Bank  will sell 20 billion yuan
($3.1 billion) each of three-year fixed-rate bonds and five-year
floating-rate notes.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.85
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.5325 per dollar.  Malaysia: The government will auction 3 billion ringgit
($990 million) of bonds maturing in April 2026. Bidding ends at
11:30 a.m. in  Kuala Lumpur .  The yield on the 4.16 percent note due July 2021 was 4.09
percent. The ringgit was at 3.0230 per dollar.  Singapore : The government will release an advance estimate
of economic growth for the first quarter at 8 a.m. local time.
Gross domestic product probably rose at an annual pace of 11.4
percent versus 3.9 percent in the last quarter of 2010,
according to a Bloomberg survey of economists.  The Monetary Authority of Singapore will announce its
currency policy at the same time.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.435 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2561.  South Korea : The government will report March department-
store sales, which rose 5.2 percent in February versus 24
percent the previous month.  The yield on the 5 percent bond due June 2020 was 4.49
percent. The won was at 1,087.93 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in Singapore at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
